\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. D. floribundum} (Haw.) Schwantes,{\i  Zeitschr. Sukkulentenk. }{\b 3:} 29 (1927) ({\i D. candens }(Haw.) Schwantes). Stems procumbent or trailing, much-branched, hirsute, not rooting freely at the nodes. Leaves 0·5-2·5(-3) cm, almost cylindrical, densely tuberculate-papillose. Flowers solitary, 1-2·5 cm in diameter; petals whitish or pink. 2n = 36.{\i  Cultivated for ornament, and naturalized on coastal rocks and walls in W. Europe.} [Az Br Ga ?Hs Lu.] ({\i South Africa}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. D. hispidum} (L.) Schwantes, {\i loc. cit.} (1927) ({\i Mesembryanthemum hispidum} L.). Stems erect or trailing, hispid, the lower branches sometimes rooting at the nodes. Leaves 1·2-3 cm, tuberculate-papillose, often reddish. Flowers solitary or 2 or 3 together, 2·5-3 cm in diameter; petals purple.{\i  Cultivated for ornament, and locally naturalized on coasts of W. Mediterranean region}. [Bl Hs It.] ({\i South Africa}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 5.            Aptenia  }              N.E. Br.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By †T.G. Tutin
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Like {\i Mesembryanthemum} but with 4 stigmas and a 4-locular capsule; valves without wings.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. A. cordifolia} (L fil.) Schwantes,{\i  Gartenfl.}{\b  77:} 69 (1928). Procumbent perennial; stems 20-60 cm, much-branched. Leaves opposite, ovate-cordate, finely papillose, flat, not glaucous. Flowers solitary, axillary and terminal, pedunculate; petals purple. 2n = 18. {\i Naturalized in open ground on coasts of S. & W. Europe}. [Az Bl Br Cr Ga Hs It Lu Si.] ({\i South Africa.})
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 6.             Disphyma  }           N.E. Br.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By D.A. Webb (Ed.1) revised by J.R. Akeroyd (Ed.2)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Like {\i Mesembryanthemum} but sprawling shrubs; glabrous, not papillose; wings on capsule widely separated at the base; apical tubercles of capsule bifid.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. D. crassifolium} (L.) L. Bolus,{\i  Fl. Pl. S. Afr.}{\b  7:} t. 276 (1927) ({\i Mesembryanthemum crassifolium} L.). Perennial; stems 20-100 cm, procumbent or trailing, rooting freely at the nodes. Leaves in groups of 3-10, 15-40 × 3-10 mm, oblanceolate, flat above, rounded or somewhat keeled beneath, with rounded apex, yellowish-green to reddish. Flowers solitary, axillary, 3-5 cm in diameter; petals purple. 2n = 36.{\i  Cultivated for ornament, and naturalized on coastal cliffs and sands in W. Europe, northwards to N. Wales.} [Az Br Ga Lu.] ({\i South Africa}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 7.           Lampranthus}         N.E. Br.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By D.A. Webb (Ed.1) revised by J.R. Akeroyd (Ed.2)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Like{\i  Mesembryanthemum} but shrubs; glabrous, not papillose; leaves opposite, slightly connate, more or less 3-angled; flowers solitary or 2 or 3 together, terminal, the petals longer than the sepals; stigmas large, conspicuous, surrounded by a raised nectary-ring; ovary semi-inferior. ({\i Oscularia} Schwantes.)
\par

