\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 8.          Erepsia}             N.E. Br.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By C.D. Preston
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Like {\i Mesembryanthemum} but shrubs; glabrous, not papillose; leaves opposite, slightly connate, acutely 3-angled; flowers solitary, or 2 or 3 together; stigmas more or less globular, very small; nectary glands minute, inconspicuous.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. E. heteropetala} (Haw.) Schwantes,{\i  Gartenfl.}{\b  77:} 68 (1928). Stems up to 35 cm, erect or decumbent. Leaves 16-30 × 6-13 mm narrowly obovoid, irregularly denticulate on the angles, pruinose. Flowers terminal, 1-1·5 cm in diameter; petals purple, shorter than the sepals; inner petals erect or inflexed; staminodes numerous. 2n = 18.{\i  Naturalized on coastal cliffs in S.W. England} ({\i Isles of Scilly}). [Br.] ({\i South Africa}.)
\par

